  {:timestamp "2026-06-29T21:30Z"
   :activity "Key findings and implications"
   :findings
   ["1. CAPACITY EXHAUSTION: Resolver capacity guards are effective. An attacker cannot permanently block legitimate disputes by filling resolver capacity, because each escrow eventually resolves and frees capacity. However, the attacker can delay the legitimate dispute by the duration of a full dispute lifecycle."
    "2. APPEAL WINDOW BOUNDARY: The >= comparison on appeal-deadline is correct. No off-by-one vulnerability — boundary is enforced at exact block-time match."
    "3. ESCALATION CHAIN INTEGRITY: Full L0→L1→L2 chain works correctly with reversal slashing at each level. L2 immediate execution prevents infinite escalation loops."
    "4. CONCURRENT RESOLUTION SAFETY: The clear-pending-settlement pattern in execute-resolution allows second resolution to overwrite first without double-settlement risk. Single resolution per level is not enforced, but the pending settlement mechanism ensures only one final outcome."
    "5. GOVERNANCE ROTATION GUARDS: Rotation is correctly blocked when pending settlement exists (prevents orphaned settlements). Rotation before first resolution works cleanly."
    "6. CIRCUIT BREAKER: New disputes are blocked while existing disputes continue. Circuit breaker protects the system from resolving disputes when resolver availability is compromised."
    "7. SLASH APPEAL BOND REFUND: Full lifecycle works — propose → appeal (bond posted) → resolve (bond refunded if upheld). Claimable mechanism correctly handles bond return."]
   :implications
   ["The dispute resolution mechanism shows good structural integrity across all tested attack surfaces"
    "The escalation chain + reversal slashing combination provides strong economic disincentives for biased rulings"
    "Circuit breaker + capacity limits + bond sybil scaling form an effective multi-layer defense against griefing"
    "Potential vulnerability: auto-track reversal slashing fires before the escrow finalizes — if the escrow is later reversed again (L0→L1→L2), the L0 slash is already executed and cannot be reversed even if L2 agrees with L0"]}

